Process Hazard Analysis
BPEP has a comprehensive program to help ensure that hazards associated with the various processes are identified and controlled. Within this program, each process is systematically examined to identify hazards and ensure that adequate controls are in place to manage these hazards. BPEP primarily uses the Knowledge-Based and Guideword Hazard and Operability (HAZOP) studies to perform these evaluations. HAZOP analysis is recognized as a systematic and thorough hazard evaluation technique. These analyses are conducted using a team of people who have operating experience and engineering expertise on the process to be evaluated. The PHA team identifies and evaluates hazards on the process as well as accident prevention and mitigation measures, and may make suggestions for additional prevention and/or mitigation measures.

To ensure that the process controls are consistent with design safety features, the BPEP periodically updates and revalidates the hazard analysis results. In addition to these periodic reviews, hazard reviews are also performed during the design stage of new facilities and for facilities undergoing significant modification.

Operating Procedures
BPEP maintains written procedures that address various modes of process operations, such as;
(1)	startup;
(2)	normal operations; 
(3)	shutdown;
(4) 	emergency operations; and,
(5) 	emergency shutdown. 

These procedures are used as a reference by experienced operators and provide a consistent basis for training of new operators. The procedures are kept current and accurate by revising them as necessary to reflect changes made through the management of change process. These procedures are periodi

cally reviewed and annually certified as current and accurate.

BPEP has identified Operating Envelopes; i.e., documented safety-related limits for specific process parameters such as temperature, level, and compositions. This information, along with written operating procedures, is readily available to operators in the process unit and for other personnel to use as necessary to safely perform their job tasks.

Training
BPEP's employees are trained to safely perform their assigned tasks. Our training program includes initial training as well as periodic refresher training and training updates when major process or equipment changes are made. 

Training is also provided for each employee involved in maintaining the ongoing integrity of process equipment. This training includes an overview of BPEPs manufacturing process and its hazards. Training is provided on specific procedures applicable to the employee's job tasks to assure that the employees can perform the job tasks in a safe manner.

Contractors
BPEP uses contractors to supplement its workforce where appropriate. Contractors are to adhere to all safety rules and practices applicable to ExxonMobil employees, as well as their own safety rules and practices. Because some contractors work on or near process equipment, BPEP has procedures in place to ensure that contractors:
(1)	perform their work in a safe manner;
(2)	have the appropriate knowledge and skills;
(3)	are aware of the hazards in their work area;
(4)	understand what they should do in the event of an emergency;
(5)	understand and follow site safety rules; and,
(6)	inform BPEP personnel of any hazards that they find during work.

This is accomplished by providing contractors with:
(1)	a process overview;
(2)	information about safety and health hazards;
(3)	emergency response plan requirements; and,
(4)	safe work practices prior to their beginning work.

In addition, BPEP evaluates contractor safety programs and performance during the selection of a contr

actor. ExxonMobil personnel monitor contractor performance to confirm that contractors are fulfilling their safety obligations.

Pre-startup and Safety Reviews (PSSRs)
BPEP conducts a PSSR for any new facility or facility modification that requires a change in the process safety information controlled by management of change (MOC). The purpose of the PSSR is to ensure that safety features, procedures, personnel, and the equipment are appropriately prepared for startup prior to placing the equipment into service. The review provides an additional check to ensure construction is in accordance with design specifications and that all supporting systems are operationally ready. The PSSR review team uses checklists to verify all aspects of readiness. A PSSR involves field verification of the construction and serves as a quality assurance function by requiring verification that accident prevention program requirements are properly implemented.

Mechanical Integrity
BPEP employs extensive mechanical integrity and preventive maintenance programs to ensure the integrity of process equipment and safety systems. Our mechanical integrity program uses equipment surveillance and preventive maintenance techniques to identify preventative maintenance opportunities before failure occurs. This program also specifies the repairs needed to return equipment to acceptable specifications.

The basic aspects of this program include:
(1)	conducting training;
(2)	developing written procedures;
(3)	performing inspections and tests;
(4)	correcting identified deficiencies; and,
(5)	applying quality assurance measures.

